[ProMED-mail is grateful to Adam Rash for the above firsthand, comprehensive update of the EIV H3N8 Florida clade 1 (FC1) event in the UK, which started early 2019. This clarifies the media-derived data included in 20190717.6571739.

Subscribers are encouraged to access the continuously updated website of AHT at https://www.aht.org.uk/disease-surveillance/equiflunet. All outbreaks are mapped and included in tables.

According to the most recent update (19 Jul 2019), since 1 Jul 2019, 43 new outbreaks have been confirmed. Each new outbreak is described in detail, including the vaccination status of the affected animals, put on the map and tabled.

Out of the 43 July outbreaks, as of 19 Jul 2019, 35 are known to have involved unvaccinated horses. The details of the 2 most recent outbreaks, included in the update, are the following:

"208. Gwent
On 17 Jul 2019, AHT confirmed an outbreak of EI on a premises in Gwent, south Wales. The one laboratory-confirmed positive is an unvaccinated non-thoroughbred that had clinical signs of coughing and lymph node enlargement. It is reported that the one other horse on the premise has demonstrated similar clinical signs. The likely source of the infection is through direct contact with a group of horses in the next door field that had been noted coughing, but have not been investigated as to the underlying cause. The positive diagnosis was confirmed by PCR on a nasopharyngeal swab.

"209. Lancashire
On 18 Jul 2019, AHT confirmed an outbreak of EI on a premises in Lancashire. The one laboratory-confirmed positive is an unvaccinated non-thoroughbred that had clinical signs of coughing, nasal discharge and pyrexia. It is reported that 2 other horses among approximately 15 horses on the premises have had clinical signs. The likely source of the infection is not known but the majority of horses on the premises are unvaccinated and some animals are believed to have recently attended local events. The positive diagnosis was confirmed by PCR on a nasopharyngeal swab."

The July 2019 update is accessible at https://www.aht.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/Equiflunet-update-19JUL19.pdf. - Mod.AS

